		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">There are good reasons to set January 1, 1997, as the dividing line between the NES's original commercial era and the homebrew era.</div><br />Sure, why not? But that doesn't make NES games developed after this date any less real.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">BootlegGames makes a distinction between homebrew and unlicensed games: the latter are developed as a day job.</div><br />True. The main differences between homebrew programmers and developers of unlicensed games are that homebrew programmers usually have less hours, work under less pressure, and have more creative freedom. That's not set in stone though... some people have more free time and/or are more focused than others, and homebrew programmers who take commissions will certainly be under more pressure and have less creative freedom.

		

		</td>
